,13346,"Allow CLI -c to resolve user Site Manager entries by name without requiring the 0/ prefix, while preserving existing 0/ functionality.",FileZilla Client,,Feature request,,new,2026-02-08T09:42:31+01:00,2026-02-08T09:42:31+01:00,"Currently, connecting to a saved Site Manager entry via the command line requires
using the internal user-site root prefix:

    filezilla.exe -c ""0/SiteName""

While functional and documented, this exposes an internal numeric root index (""0"")
that is not represented in the UI. The UI presents saved entries under “My Sites”
without referencing this internal structure.

Even for experienced CLI users, requiring knowledge of an internal tree index
introduces unnecessary coupling to implementation details. This proposal does not
aim to simplify the CLI or remove explicit control. It aims to reduce reliance on
internal indexing knowledge when resolution is unambiguous.

Proposal:

Allow both forms to work:

    -c ""0/SiteName""      (existing behavior, unchanged)
    -c ""SiteName""        (implicitly resolved under user-site root)

If no numeric root prefix is provided, the CLI would default to resolving
the site under the user-site root.

Edge Case Handling:

- If predefined and user sites share the same name, explicit numeric prefixes
  (e.g., ""0/"" or ""1/"") would continue to override resolution exactly as today.
- Only when no numeric prefix is provided would implicit resolution be attempted.
- If no match is found under the user-site root, existing error behavior remains unchanged.

Design Considerations:

- This change preserves full backward compatibility.
- No modification to internal storage, indexing, or tree structure is required.
- Explicit control remains available at all times.
- This does not reduce precision; it reduces unnecessary ceremony.

If maintainers are open to the idea, I am willing to submit a minimal patch
implementing this fallback resolution logic along with thorough testing
to ensure no regressions are introduced.

The intent is to improve CLI ergonomics while preserving the project’s
existing explicit design philosophy.",Lee Linkoff
