,13356,Add record_size_limit TLS extension (RFC 8449) to ClientHello for IoT interoperability,FileZilla Client,,Feature request,,new,2026-03-27T01:54:46+01:00,2026-03-27T01:54:46+01:00,"FileZilla does not advertise the `record_size_limit` TLS extension (RFC 8449) in ClientHello messages, even though GnuTLS - FileZilla's TLS library - already implements it. This creates an interoperability gap with memory-constrained IoT devices that depend on this extension to function correctly over TLS.

RFC 8449 defines `record_size_limit` as the modern replacement for `max_fragment_length` (RFC 6066). It allows TLS endpoints to negotiate a maximum protected record size smaller than the default 16,384 bytes, which many microcontrollers cannot buffer for decryption due to RAM constraints. The extension is symmetric: each side independently advertises the maximum record size it is willing to receive, so advertising the full 16,384 bytes on FileZilla's side has zero performance or memory impact - it purely enables servers to communicate their own limit back.

Per RFC 8449 Section 4: ""Endpoints SHOULD advertise the `record_size_limit` extension, even if they have no need to limit the size of records. For clients, this allows servers to advertise a limit at their discretion.""

The EU Cyber Resilience Act (2027) requires IoT devices to implement secure communications, making this interoperability gap increasingly relevant. The fix on FileZilla's side should be straightforward: GnuTLS supports the extension via `gnutls_record_set_max_size()`, and calling it with the maximum permissible value (16,384 bytes) before the handshake would cause the extension to be advertised without changing any actual behaviour.

In fact I've just added TLS support to our own open-source controllers, which do not have enough RAM to offer full 16K TLS data buffers, so I can't upload files longer than ~1K yet. Hence it would really help if this could be addressed in FTPS. I'd be happy to provide a patch as well if this is any help.",chrishamm
